1
00:00:00,211 --> 00:00:10,857
[SPEAKER_02]: Welcome everyone to the meeting of the Metro Charter Study Committee's Subcommittee on Articles 2 and 3.

2
00:00:11,577 --> 00:00:15,380
[SPEAKER_02]: So first order of business is to accept the minutes from November 30th.

3
00:00:15,880 --> 00:00:17,801
[SPEAKER_02]: Did everyone look at those?

4
00:00:19,422 --> 00:00:19,722
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay.

5
00:00:20,222 --> 00:00:21,723
[SPEAKER_02]: Do we have a motion to accept?

6
00:00:22,624 --> 00:00:24,264
[SPEAKER_04]: I would like to make a motion to accept.

7
00:00:24,885 --> 00:00:25,165
[SPEAKER_02]: Great.

8
00:00:25,605 --> 00:00:27,166
[SPEAKER_02]: John, are you able to unmute?

9
00:00:27,666 --> 00:00:27,866
[SPEAKER_02]: Second.

10
00:00:28,147 --> 00:00:28,507
[SPEAKER_04]: I am now.

11
00:00:29,693 --> 00:00:29,993
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay.

12
00:00:30,293 --> 00:00:30,914
[SPEAKER_02]: All in favor?

13
00:00:30,934 --> 00:00:32,034
[SPEAKER_02]: Aye.

14
00:00:32,335 --> 00:00:32,655
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay.

15
00:00:32,815 --> 00:00:33,035
[SPEAKER_02]: Great.

16
00:00:34,136 --> 00:00:35,296
[SPEAKER_02]: Minutes accepted.

17
00:00:35,757 --> 00:00:36,937
[SPEAKER_02]: Awesome.

18
00:00:37,778 --> 00:00:38,378
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay.

19
00:00:38,398 --> 00:00:48,544
[SPEAKER_02]: So we, we had a couple of questions left over from our last meeting, and then we also had some things come up from the full committee meeting.

20
00:00:50,465 --> 00:00:57,069
[SPEAKER_02]: So, um, I mean, we can go in the order of the agenda or we can sort of check in because David, you were going to, um,

21
00:00:58,419 --> 00:01:01,542
[SPEAKER_02]: you were going to work on creating a document, right?

22
00:01:01,842 --> 00:01:03,003
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah.

23
00:01:03,103 --> 00:01:08,129
[SPEAKER_04]: I just spent the last 45 minutes working on that, and I'm partway through Article 2.

24
00:01:08,729 --> 00:01:10,471
[SPEAKER_04]: Still not even all the way through that.

25
00:01:12,353 --> 00:01:20,802
[SPEAKER_02]: Well, one of the things I thought we should do after the full committee meeting was review the recommendations for removals.

26
00:01:23,524 --> 00:01:30,670
[SPEAKER_02]: So I don't know if, David, you had a chance to look at the minutes or to sort of see what some of the discussion points were.

27
00:01:32,271 --> 00:01:36,514
[SPEAKER_02]: But, John, you were there.

28
00:01:36,614 --> 00:01:44,881
[SPEAKER_02]: So do we just want to sort of re-look at that based on the feedback from that?

29
00:01:46,162 --> 00:01:46,862
[SPEAKER_03]: I think it's reasonable.

30
00:01:47,483 --> 00:01:49,404
[SPEAKER_03]: I thought it was a real concern.

31
00:01:49,444 --> 00:01:52,346
[SPEAKER_03]: I think we even talked about, David, the concern

32
00:01:53,609 --> 00:01:55,471
[SPEAKER_03]: was limiting the executive's power.

33
00:01:56,011 --> 00:01:58,434
[SPEAKER_03]: And I think that's something we had even talked about internally.

34
00:02:01,056 --> 00:02:02,137
[SPEAKER_03]: So I was sympathetic to it.

35
00:02:02,677 --> 00:02:03,578
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm open to it.

36
00:02:03,698 --> 00:02:10,385
[SPEAKER_03]: I think I'd have to refresh, and I did it.

37
00:02:11,966 --> 00:02:16,170
[SPEAKER_03]: I'd have to refresh what other communities do relative to the city council.

38
00:02:18,607 --> 00:02:28,772
[SPEAKER_03]: appointments, I think they all generally sent them to, I think we just sort of copied and pasted on appointments, but then removals, we beefed up to comfortable.

39
00:02:28,972 --> 00:02:32,874
[SPEAKER_03]: I would be comfortable taking a step back and mirroring other communities.

40
00:02:34,214 --> 00:02:34,595
[SPEAKER_01]: Okay.

41
00:02:35,115 --> 00:02:40,737
[SPEAKER_03]: I'd be interested in hearing what you think, but I still always start with the baseline.

42
00:02:40,757 --> 00:02:43,799
[SPEAKER_03]: I like stealing from other communities when it seems to be working and, um,

43
00:02:45,517 --> 00:02:46,898
[SPEAKER_03]: You know, I know we've all shared.

44
00:02:47,018 --> 00:02:48,159
[SPEAKER_03]: Oh, I'm sorry, I keep cutting you off.

45
00:02:48,259 --> 00:02:50,381
[SPEAKER_02]: No, no, that's okay.

46
00:02:51,361 --> 00:02:52,082
[SPEAKER_02]: David, go ahead.

47
00:02:53,203 --> 00:03:03,110
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah, so I think when we talked last time, we already kind of pulled it back and just said that city councils can remove by unanimous vote.

48
00:03:04,071 --> 00:03:06,053
[SPEAKER_04]: Right.

49
00:03:06,113 --> 00:03:08,915
[SPEAKER_04]: Multi-member boards and commissions, but not department heads.

50
00:03:09,195 --> 00:03:13,018
[SPEAKER_04]: And if we want to pull that back even further, I think that's fine.

51
00:03:14,140 --> 00:03:27,069
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, I mean, I think there were, so there was definitely the concern, John, that you mentioned about limiting the executive's power, but I feel like there was also concerns raised about legality issues, right?

52
00:03:27,169 --> 00:03:42,880
[SPEAKER_02]: Because, you know, to have the power to remove given to a body that didn't make the appointment, kind of, could be a potential issue.

53
00:03:44,722 --> 00:03:46,383
[SPEAKER_03]: I suppose it could be, I guess.

54
00:03:46,463 --> 00:03:50,684
[SPEAKER_02]: And the Collins Center said there might be some case law, but I don't know.

55
00:03:50,884 --> 00:03:52,365
[SPEAKER_02]: They didn't give us a specific reference.

56
00:03:53,025 --> 00:04:04,988
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, my memory is, again, this is generally, if you appoint someone to a multi-member body for a set term, you can't remove them unless you provide for how they're removed.

57
00:04:06,049 --> 00:04:11,210
[SPEAKER_03]: So I don't know if there's any case law limiting a statute's ability to dictate how they're removed.

58
00:04:12,211 --> 00:04:13,131
[SPEAKER_03]: I'd be interested to see it.

59
00:04:14,548 --> 00:04:20,951
[SPEAKER_03]: My memory was always that you sort of, when you're creating the charter or statute, whatever, you set the terms of it.

60
00:04:24,493 --> 00:04:24,793
[SPEAKER_02]: Right.

61
00:04:25,414 --> 00:04:25,714
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah.

62
00:04:25,934 --> 00:04:33,218
[SPEAKER_02]: And I think, my understanding was they were talking about, because the city council wouldn't be the appointing body,

63
00:04:34,167 --> 00:04:38,850
[SPEAKER_02]: that then giving that body the power to remove could present issues.

64
00:04:38,890 --> 00:04:42,493
[SPEAKER_02]: But I could be misinterpreting or misunderstanding, but that's why.

65
00:04:42,933 --> 00:04:45,455
[SPEAKER_03]: They definitely were curious about it, which I think is fair.

66
00:04:45,896 --> 00:04:46,936
[SPEAKER_03]: My memory is it was novel.

67
00:04:47,256 --> 00:04:51,079
[SPEAKER_03]: But I don't remember exactly what the legal issue was.

68
00:04:51,319 --> 00:04:51,920
[SPEAKER_03]: I'd be interested.

69
00:04:52,160 --> 00:04:53,481
[SPEAKER_03]: I always think this stuff is interesting.

70
00:04:53,821 --> 00:04:54,181
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah.

71
00:04:57,204 --> 00:04:58,505
[SPEAKER_02]: They were definitely vague on it.

72
00:04:58,605 --> 00:05:02,808
[SPEAKER_02]: They kind of implied that it could be there, but there was some vagueness to it.

73
00:05:08,930 --> 00:05:29,148
[SPEAKER_02]: I feel like I've seen some charters that, I haven't seen any that give council removal authority, but I have seen some sections that give the person who's being removed the right to a hearing, which usually then I think happens before the council.

74
00:05:33,277 --> 00:05:39,883
[SPEAKER_04]: I think that I didn't see the call center kind of like directly pushing back against this as a bad idea.

75
00:05:39,943 --> 00:05:41,945
[SPEAKER_04]: So I don't really know of any reason why we.

76
00:05:43,226 --> 00:05:45,268
[SPEAKER_04]: Like, I don't have a strong feeling that we need to change it.

77
00:05:45,288 --> 00:05:55,197
[SPEAKER_04]: You know, I'm comfortable with the way we decided it to be, but certainly if it's going to get the city into legal hot water, we shouldn't do it.

78
00:05:55,337 --> 00:05:59,281
[SPEAKER_04]: But I don't feel like the call center gave us exactly that pushback.

79
00:06:02,038 --> 00:06:10,721
[SPEAKER_02]: They didn't say that directly, but they raised the question about it.

80
00:06:11,562 --> 00:06:16,764
[SPEAKER_02]: But we also had some committee members who raised strong objections to it.

81
00:06:17,544 --> 00:06:28,748
[SPEAKER_02]: So, I mean, obviously, this is, you know, one of the things that I want to do tonight is figure out how we're going to present this issue for a vote because,

82
00:06:30,112 --> 00:06:40,040
[SPEAKER_02]: There's different components of this section regarding multi-member boards.

83
00:06:41,221 --> 00:06:45,204
[SPEAKER_02]: I'm guessing that committee members might want to vote on some of them separately.

84
00:06:45,224 --> 00:06:50,229
[SPEAKER_02]: This piece might not go along with it, but it might go along with the rest.

85
00:06:51,430 --> 00:06:51,790
[SPEAKER_02]: That's all.

86
00:06:53,051 --> 00:06:54,632
[SPEAKER_04]: I think the thing that makes the most sense is,

87
00:06:56,642 --> 00:07:03,105
[SPEAKER_04]: When I or we finish writing, you know, our 1st draft of these sections.

88
00:07:03,786 --> 00:07:06,927
[SPEAKER_04]: We just send it to the large and say, like.

89
00:07:07,488 --> 00:07:14,431
[SPEAKER_04]: We'd love some feedback and we'd love, you know, let's come up with a list of of changes that people are interested in discussing or voting on.

90
00:07:17,230 --> 00:07:27,498
[SPEAKER_04]: Certainly, I don't think we want to be bullheaded and ignore the greater group's thoughts on these types of things.

91
00:07:27,578 --> 00:07:40,528
[SPEAKER_04]: But also, I don't know that we need to kind of shrink from... I don't know that we need to be afraid of them making different decisions in the whole group than we made in the small group, if that makes sense.

92
00:07:43,410 --> 00:07:43,730
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah.

93
00:07:43,790 --> 00:07:44,651
[SPEAKER_02]: John, did you have a thought?

94
00:07:45,281 --> 00:07:46,402
[SPEAKER_03]: No, I think that's fair.

95
00:07:48,303 --> 00:07:49,124
[SPEAKER_03]: But I will say I did.

96
00:07:51,226 --> 00:07:56,810
[SPEAKER_03]: I guess I appreciated what they were saying more than just sort of.

97
00:07:56,830 --> 00:07:58,211
[SPEAKER_04]: And I'm sorry to have missed that meeting.

98
00:07:58,652 --> 00:07:59,572
[SPEAKER_04]: Was it recorded?

99
00:08:00,193 --> 00:08:01,914
[SPEAKER_02]: Yes, I think they should be.

100
00:08:02,034 --> 00:08:02,575
[SPEAKER_02]: It should be up.

101
00:08:04,923 --> 00:08:09,285
[SPEAKER_03]: I did want to share, because I had a thought similar to David as far as approach.

102
00:08:09,365 --> 00:08:13,467
[SPEAKER_03]: I do think it's always, at least for me, difficult to wrap my head around things in the abstract.

103
00:08:13,487 --> 00:08:25,651
[SPEAKER_03]: So to the extent we can put language together, share it in advance, and then say, let's talk about this concrete provision, I think that is helpful.

104
00:08:26,912 --> 00:08:32,214
[SPEAKER_02]: So you're talking about language just from whatever section this is to dash

105
00:08:34,643 --> 00:08:35,504
[SPEAKER_02]: 10, whatever it is.

106
00:08:37,725 --> 00:08:38,185
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay.

107
00:08:38,765 --> 00:08:41,866
[SPEAKER_02]: So we can do that.

108
00:08:42,266 --> 00:08:48,829
[SPEAKER_02]: I would like to be able to send it to the committee this week for our next meeting, just this particular section.

109
00:08:51,070 --> 00:08:55,052
[SPEAKER_02]: And maybe another one if we can decide on something that we think is ready.

110
00:08:55,072 --> 00:09:01,234
[SPEAKER_04]: I mean, my hope was that by Monday, I was hoping to have all of

111
00:09:03,573 --> 00:09:06,315
[SPEAKER_04]: Articles 2 and 3 done, especially, I mean.

112
00:09:07,156 --> 00:09:12,761
[SPEAKER_04]: Having worked on this for an hour, the majority of the work is copying and pasting and making sure that there isn't anything.

113
00:09:12,781 --> 00:09:20,167
[SPEAKER_04]: Uh, you know, making sure if that city council consistently making sure that counselor is spelled consistently.

114
00:09:21,008 --> 00:09:26,653
[SPEAKER_04]: And then just, you know, kind of checking it against the decisions we made to make updates.

115
00:09:27,365 --> 00:09:30,248
[SPEAKER_04]: So it's pretty quick work, all things considered.

116
00:09:30,508 --> 00:09:30,928
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay.

117
00:09:31,409 --> 00:09:35,712
[SPEAKER_02]: I mean, and these are two very important weighty sections of the charter.

118
00:09:35,732 --> 00:09:45,740
[SPEAKER_02]: And I don't know that we're going to go through every, I mean, some of the sections we may just sort of, as a committee, decide, okay, this we're going to use standard language.

119
00:09:45,900 --> 00:09:51,665
[SPEAKER_02]: And the Collins Center is available to do the draft, do some of the drafting for us too.

120
00:09:54,583 --> 00:09:59,664
[SPEAKER_02]: But if this is fine to go to approach these two sections this way.

121
00:10:01,024 --> 00:10:13,126
[SPEAKER_02]: So I guess I just want to circle back to the removal procedure because we did hear at least two committee members raised strong objections to it.

122
00:10:13,466 --> 00:10:21,788
[SPEAKER_02]: And so the question is, do we want to, and given the concerns that were raised, do we want to take that out

123
00:10:22,615 --> 00:10:25,896
[SPEAKER_02]: in the draft that we are going to give the committee?

124
00:10:27,577 --> 00:10:28,597
[SPEAKER_04]: I'd prefer not to.

125
00:10:29,437 --> 00:10:38,600
[SPEAKER_04]: Personally, I'd be more comfortable with a full vote, especially because I think it's so much easier to kind of present a maximalist draft.

126
00:10:39,200 --> 00:10:43,261
[SPEAKER_04]: It's so easy to take a vote to strike that sentence or that other sentence.

127
00:10:43,341 --> 00:10:49,583
[SPEAKER_04]: And it's a lot trickier, I think, to have a group discussion with 11 people or however many people are there about

128
00:10:50,183 --> 00:10:53,846
[SPEAKER_04]: How we're going to phrase the addition, so I'd rather keep it in like.

129
00:10:54,586 --> 00:11:00,230
[SPEAKER_04]: If we, as a group, you know, I think it's a good thing if if you and John and Eunice think that, like.

130
00:11:00,710 --> 00:11:03,192
[SPEAKER_04]: This is actually not a power we want to give the city council.

131
00:11:03,812 --> 00:11:07,235
[SPEAKER_04]: Of course, like, I think we should do what we think as a group, but.

132
00:11:08,075 --> 00:11:11,878
[SPEAKER_04]: If we are still happy with giving that power, I think we should keep it in.

133
00:11:13,511 --> 00:11:22,333
[SPEAKER_02]: I guess I'm feeling after hearing, you know, some of the concerns that the Collins Center raised, I would probably vote to take it out.

134
00:11:22,533 --> 00:11:30,795
[SPEAKER_02]: But if we want to see what the whole committee thinks, that's, you know, I think that's fine.

135
00:11:32,315 --> 00:11:32,576
[SPEAKER_04]: John?

136
00:11:33,816 --> 00:11:42,638
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, I guess my thought, at least when it comes to the unanimous city council removal, is even I think when we talked about it, I thought it would be unlikely to ever happen.

137
00:11:44,432 --> 00:11:55,138
[SPEAKER_03]: So to the extent that that is causing people concern, I guess if I never thought we were going to do it anyway because the problem would be resolved then, I think the, so I would be fine.

138
00:11:55,738 --> 00:11:57,179
[SPEAKER_03]: I guess I don't feel strongly about it either way.

139
00:11:57,219 --> 00:12:02,062
[SPEAKER_03]: I don't know how I'd vote on it, but I'm fine dropping it, I guess is what I would say.

140
00:12:03,242 --> 00:12:08,405
[SPEAKER_03]: I think the larger concern would be review of appointments.

141
00:12:09,446 --> 00:12:11,047
[SPEAKER_03]: You know, I think that is a more substantive,

142
00:12:12,583 --> 00:12:15,584
[SPEAKER_03]: and to what extent do we want some oversight?

143
00:12:15,644 --> 00:12:23,706
[SPEAKER_03]: Maybe it's not even what we talked about the first time of city council members having oversight and removal.

144
00:12:24,687 --> 00:12:27,507
[SPEAKER_03]: I think that always seemed like the realer provision to me.

145
00:12:29,128 --> 00:12:34,389
[SPEAKER_03]: And I do think the both items were sort of getting conflated a little bit.

146
00:12:34,409 --> 00:12:38,610
[SPEAKER_03]: So I don't know, I guess I don't have any answer.

147
00:12:38,790 --> 00:12:40,571
[SPEAKER_03]: So I'm sorry for being so squishy.

148
00:12:41,262 --> 00:12:43,405
[SPEAKER_02]: Can you say how you think they were being conflated?

149
00:12:43,765 --> 00:12:47,530
[SPEAKER_03]: Well, I just, it just, again, because we're talking the abstract.

150
00:12:48,451 --> 00:12:54,238
[SPEAKER_03]: I seem to remember at one point trying to talk about there's two different avenues we were creating for removal.

151
00:12:58,163 --> 00:12:58,964
[SPEAKER_03]: So maybe we made it.

152
00:13:01,213 --> 00:13:04,434
[SPEAKER_03]: I don't know that anyone's opinion has changed versus one or the other, to be clear.

153
00:13:04,454 --> 00:13:20,601
[SPEAKER_02]: You're talking about the piece, there was the unanimous, the ability for the city council to initiate a removal with a unanimous vote, and then also the power to reject a removal with a majority.

154
00:13:21,422 --> 00:13:21,582
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah.

155
00:13:24,364 --> 00:13:30,470
[SPEAKER_03]: So I don't know even how we feel about, I think even in this meeting, we've just talked about the unanimous removal.

156
00:13:30,490 --> 00:13:31,451
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, we have, right.

157
00:13:31,951 --> 00:13:40,599
[SPEAKER_02]: I guess I feel like when it comes to a vote, I will probably vote not to give the removal powers to the city council.

158
00:13:40,619 --> 00:13:42,401
[SPEAKER_03]: Okay.

159
00:13:44,983 --> 00:13:48,587
[SPEAKER_02]: But that doesn't mean if other people will agree with me, so.

160
00:13:50,662 --> 00:13:52,283
[SPEAKER_04]: Let's just take a quick vote right now.

161
00:13:52,804 --> 00:13:55,085
[SPEAKER_04]: Should we leave it in our draft or not?

162
00:13:56,266 --> 00:14:00,568
[SPEAKER_04]: So I guess a motion to vote on leaving it or taking it out of the draft.

163
00:14:01,008 --> 00:14:09,693
[SPEAKER_02]: And when you say, are you saying to take out both removal precisions or powers or one removal power?

164
00:14:10,934 --> 00:14:15,396
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm saying to remove the removal by unanimous vote of the city council.

165
00:14:15,676 --> 00:14:15,957
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay.

166
00:14:18,714 --> 00:14:19,074
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay.

167
00:14:19,114 --> 00:14:30,600
[SPEAKER_02]: So the motion is to remove the provision from suggested draft, which gives council power to initiate a removal with a unanimous vote.

168
00:14:31,601 --> 00:14:31,841
[SPEAKER_04]: Yes.

169
00:14:32,862 --> 00:14:33,262
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay.

170
00:14:35,243 --> 00:14:36,284
[SPEAKER_02]: Does anybody second that?

171
00:14:36,304 --> 00:14:38,525
[SPEAKER_03]: I'll second it.

172
00:14:39,205 --> 00:14:39,525
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay.

173
00:14:40,426 --> 00:14:45,569
[SPEAKER_02]: So all in favor of removal?

174
00:14:45,589 --> 00:14:47,690
[SPEAKER_02]: Aye.

175
00:14:48,730 --> 00:14:48,910
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah.

176
00:14:49,971 --> 00:14:51,371
[SPEAKER_02]: I'll vote to remove it.

177
00:14:51,391 --> 00:14:51,672
[SPEAKER_03]: Against?

178
00:14:53,132 --> 00:14:54,853
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm against it.

179
00:14:55,013 --> 00:14:55,494
[SPEAKER_02]: And John?

180
00:14:56,774 --> 00:14:57,555
[SPEAKER_03]: I'll vote to remove it.

181
00:14:58,535 --> 00:15:02,577
[SPEAKER_03]: Again, I don't know that it would ever even happen.

182
00:15:03,838 --> 00:15:07,160
[SPEAKER_03]: So to me, I'm fine taking it.

183
00:15:09,441 --> 00:15:09,741
[SPEAKER_02]: OK.

184
00:15:14,363 --> 00:15:17,165
[SPEAKER_02]: OK, so the motion passes 2 to 1 in favor.

185
00:15:19,945 --> 00:15:24,767
[SPEAKER_02]: And then the other piece was the ability to overturn a removal.

186
00:15:24,787 --> 00:15:32,789
[SPEAKER_02]: And that one, we have not talked about whether to leave that in or take it out.

187
00:15:37,971 --> 00:15:38,451
[SPEAKER_02]: Any thoughts?

188
00:15:41,152 --> 00:15:44,293
[SPEAKER_03]: I mean, I do like something here.

189
00:15:46,685 --> 00:15:54,690
[SPEAKER_03]: You know, even if it's, we don't call it overturning, some sort of notice, some sort of oversight, I think has value.

190
00:15:56,612 --> 00:16:05,317
[SPEAKER_03]: So, you know, I guess my inclination would be to leave this, but just to be, this is just me, you know, that I don't want to speak, but I'm open to something.

191
00:16:06,438 --> 00:16:08,279
[SPEAKER_03]: Frankly, I think there should be something.

192
00:16:09,020 --> 00:16:12,642
[SPEAKER_03]: I'll do another review in advance of that meeting of other charters.

193
00:16:15,460 --> 00:16:21,503
[SPEAKER_03]: But I think even notice is valuable, you know, to the affected party, but also the council.

194
00:16:22,143 --> 00:16:30,607
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, there's definitely, I've seen, you know, I think notice is standard language in general.

195
00:16:33,269 --> 00:16:35,310
[SPEAKER_02]: Some of these are not very searchable.

196
00:16:36,110 --> 00:16:38,111
[SPEAKER_03]: Now I'm looking at Weymouth right now and there's notice.

197
00:16:38,571 --> 00:16:41,473
[SPEAKER_03]: I don't think it mentions the council though.

198
00:16:41,493 --> 00:16:42,293
[SPEAKER_03]: I think it's just the clerk.

199
00:16:46,087 --> 00:16:46,967
[SPEAKER_02]: That could be.

200
00:16:47,627 --> 00:16:47,927
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah.

201
00:16:48,488 --> 00:16:48,948
[SPEAKER_02]: And just.

202
00:16:50,648 --> 00:16:52,989
[SPEAKER_03]: So one thing I thought was compelling was.

203
00:16:56,689 --> 00:17:02,210
[SPEAKER_02]: Hang on, I just want to, I'm sorry, I was just going to share one thing that's pertinent here.

204
00:17:04,271 --> 00:17:09,032
[SPEAKER_02]: I believe, let's see, did I just click on this is Gardner and this is an example of.

205
00:17:13,553 --> 00:17:14,253
[SPEAKER_02]: This is under.

206
00:17:17,748 --> 00:17:21,910
[SPEAKER_02]: This is, no.

207
00:17:23,050 --> 00:17:31,193
[SPEAKER_02]: The mayor may, with the approval of a majority of the members of the city council, remove any head of a department or member of a board before the expiration of term.

208
00:17:31,813 --> 00:17:33,314
[SPEAKER_02]: That members of the school committee, right.

209
00:17:34,154 --> 00:17:35,675
[SPEAKER_02]: Officers elected by the city council.

210
00:17:35,695 --> 00:17:41,157
[SPEAKER_04]: That's even more restrictive than the thing we're suggesting, right?

211
00:17:42,369 --> 00:17:44,311
[SPEAKER_02]: Well, no, I think that is what we suggested.

212
00:17:44,371 --> 00:17:48,774
[SPEAKER_02]: Well, no, no, actually, the mayor, this says the mayor has to get approval.

213
00:17:49,135 --> 00:17:50,095
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, you're right.

214
00:17:50,816 --> 00:17:58,142
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, what we suggested was that the council could override the removal, right?

215
00:17:58,523 --> 00:18:01,585
[SPEAKER_04]: And we set a high standard to the override, right, of two-thirds.

216
00:18:01,805 --> 00:18:08,091
[SPEAKER_04]: So this is, you know, effectively, the mayor would only need to convince three or four people

217
00:18:10,655 --> 00:18:13,696
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, this is where you get the right to the hearing, et cetera.

218
00:18:16,437 --> 00:18:17,197
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah.

219
00:18:20,899 --> 00:18:21,619
[SPEAKER_02]: OK.

220
00:18:22,800 --> 00:18:26,481
[SPEAKER_02]: So that's just one charter, but we could look at others.

221
00:18:26,541 --> 00:18:29,182
[SPEAKER_02]: But we can see that it's not unprecedented.

222
00:18:31,073 --> 00:18:48,157
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah, well, and, you know, the thing I like about giving the city council kind of the ability to overturn or to reject or whatever language we want to use there is, again, I think that kind of the default process should not involve city council involvement, right?

223
00:18:48,237 --> 00:18:53,219
[SPEAKER_04]: I imagine for whatever reason a person is being removed, it's not a happy, comfortable reason.

224
00:18:53,899 --> 00:18:57,880
[SPEAKER_04]: And so it's probably better not to drag them in front of the city council or to have

225
00:18:58,640 --> 00:19:01,563
[SPEAKER_04]: A big discussion and explanation and whatever else.

226
00:19:02,424 --> 00:19:02,884
[SPEAKER_01]: Exactly.

227
00:19:03,505 --> 00:19:03,785
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah.

228
00:19:03,845 --> 00:19:10,031
[SPEAKER_04]: But in the event of somebody, yeah.

229
00:19:10,611 --> 00:19:12,172
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay.

230
00:19:12,253 --> 00:19:15,535
[SPEAKER_02]: Are we good with that or leaving that in or do we want to?

231
00:19:17,497 --> 00:19:17,838
[SPEAKER_03]: I am.

232
00:19:18,558 --> 00:19:19,039
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm sorry.

233
00:19:19,079 --> 00:19:19,679
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm good with that.

234
00:19:25,455 --> 00:19:31,880
[SPEAKER_00]: things that I'm thinking about here is, to be clear, I'm not on the committee, so I'm just chiming in here.

235
00:19:33,361 --> 00:19:44,789
[SPEAKER_00]: But when you're saying that the city council can do things by vote of, are we writing in there whether it's majority or supermajority?

236
00:19:44,809 --> 00:19:52,774
[SPEAKER_00]: That means different things now when there are seven of them versus down the road when there might be 11 of them.

237
00:19:54,293 --> 00:20:01,203
[SPEAKER_00]: So, and he's saying, you know, the mayor may only need 3 or 4 people to persuade, you know, she might need 6 or 7.

238
00:20:01,964 --> 00:20:09,394
[SPEAKER_00]: If our council becomes larger, and then the other thing that I know that we were banding around.

239
00:20:09,973 --> 00:20:22,242
[SPEAKER_00]: at some point that I want to make sure that, you know, gets in there is when we're talking about how many days somebody has to do something, is it calendar days or business days?

240
00:20:22,923 --> 00:20:29,107
[SPEAKER_00]: Do we want to be ambiguous about that for, you know, somebody 10, 15 years down the road?

241
00:20:29,768 --> 00:20:33,170
[SPEAKER_00]: Or do we want to be clear that it's 10 business days?

242
00:20:34,391 --> 00:20:37,734
[SPEAKER_02]: So I think 45 was the number we had in there, right?

243
00:20:40,460 --> 00:20:44,724
[SPEAKER_02]: So we can, we can specify calendar or business.

244
00:20:45,664 --> 00:20:47,026
[SPEAKER_02]: I don't see a problem with that.

245
00:20:48,167 --> 00:20:50,248
[SPEAKER_04]: I've been thinking through this as calendar days.

246
00:20:50,348 --> 00:21:04,760
[SPEAKER_04]: I think business days, business days is like a really not, it's a weird thing to put in your charter because it would be a real dumb discussion of like, well, was this a business day?

247
00:21:04,800 --> 00:21:05,461
[SPEAKER_04]: Because for the.

248
00:21:06,148 --> 00:21:10,970
[SPEAKER_04]: The city decided it's a holiday, but for the state, it's not like no, it's just yeah.

249
00:21:11,750 --> 00:21:12,090
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay.

250
00:21:12,830 --> 00:21:16,051
[SPEAKER_02]: So, since we're talking, since we're talking about the number of days.

251
00:21:18,252 --> 00:21:26,235
[SPEAKER_02]: I mean, we settled on 45, but there were a couple of comments at the meeting that concern again about discouraging volunteerism came up.

252
00:21:28,149 --> 00:21:34,790
[SPEAKER_02]: And I think we talked about, we had talked about a shorter period of time could just be too hard, right?

253
00:21:35,151 --> 00:21:42,932
[SPEAKER_02]: I mean, but I think initially we had talked about two weeks or three weeks or something, but I guess I'm just throwing out, do we want to reduce it to 30?

254
00:21:43,172 --> 00:21:48,073
[SPEAKER_02]: I don't know.

255
00:21:48,093 --> 00:21:50,594
[SPEAKER_04]: I still have 30 days in my notes.

256
00:21:51,394 --> 00:21:52,294
[SPEAKER_02]: Oh, I thought we said 45.

257
00:21:52,414 --> 00:21:52,874
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay.

258
00:21:54,195 --> 00:21:55,375
[SPEAKER_04]: Maybe I just didn't update it.

259
00:21:56,013 --> 00:21:56,633
[SPEAKER_04]: No, no.

260
00:21:56,773 --> 00:21:57,094
[SPEAKER_04]: Probably.

261
00:21:57,114 --> 00:21:57,754
[SPEAKER_02]: I could be wrong.

262
00:21:57,834 --> 00:21:58,434
[SPEAKER_02]: I could be wrong.

263
00:21:59,495 --> 00:22:00,455
[SPEAKER_02]: What do you remember, John?

264
00:22:02,896 --> 00:22:03,476
[SPEAKER_03]: I don't remember.

265
00:22:04,077 --> 00:22:04,537
[SPEAKER_02]: OK.

266
00:22:05,097 --> 00:22:07,678
[SPEAKER_02]: Well, then it's probably 30, and I don't remember it.

267
00:22:07,758 --> 00:22:10,640
[SPEAKER_02]: OK, then I think that's reasonable.

268
00:22:10,700 --> 00:22:17,683
[SPEAKER_04]: Initially, we said like 15, and then decided the next week that 15 was actually really brief, given that.

269
00:22:17,703 --> 00:22:18,123
[SPEAKER_04]: I think it was 30.

270
00:22:18,723 --> 00:22:18,824
[SPEAKER_00]: OK.

271
00:22:18,904 --> 00:22:19,324
[SPEAKER_00]: I'm happy with 30.

272
00:22:24,539 --> 00:22:25,880
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay, I think that's fine.

273
00:22:26,120 --> 00:22:35,388
[SPEAKER_02]: I just wanted the memo that the Collins Center gave us had example language from the Somerville draft charter, which has 45.

274
00:22:36,929 --> 00:22:51,801
[SPEAKER_02]: And it basically, though, kind of says what we independently came up with, which just the mayor shall refer to the city council and file with the city clerk the name of each person the mayor desires to appoint.

275
00:22:52,838 --> 00:22:58,520
[SPEAKER_02]: City Council, this says 45 days to vote to approve or reject.

276
00:22:59,180 --> 00:23:00,581
[SPEAKER_02]: With approval, okay.

277
00:23:01,101 --> 00:23:06,383
[SPEAKER_02]: Actually, yeah, no, maybe that actually says they have to vote, so it's a little different than what we said.

278
00:23:07,504 --> 00:23:07,804
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay.

279
00:23:09,024 --> 00:23:17,648
[SPEAKER_02]: The other thing that the Collins Center gave us, which I wonder if we want to think over, is the language from the Fall River Charter about

280
00:23:20,668 --> 00:23:21,750
[SPEAKER_02]: Recruitment efforts.

281
00:23:22,351 --> 00:23:22,992
[SPEAKER_02]: Do you remember that?

282
00:23:25,055 --> 00:23:29,242
[SPEAKER_02]: We didn't include this, but they it's just.

283
00:23:30,186 --> 00:23:32,448
[SPEAKER_02]: Basically, I don't think we included it.

284
00:23:32,468 --> 00:23:33,629
[SPEAKER_02]: I hope I remember mine.

285
00:23:34,149 --> 00:23:40,835
[SPEAKER_02]: The mayor shall annually post on the city's website in February a list of all vacancies on multi-member bodies.

286
00:23:41,516 --> 00:23:45,599
[SPEAKER_02]: Such listings shall include guidance on applying to serve on a multiple-member body.

287
00:23:46,199 --> 00:23:56,108
[SPEAKER_02]: The mayor may also notify any civic, business, neighborhood, or service organizations in the city of multi-member body vacancies, members of multi-member bodies, and appointments.

288
00:23:57,760 --> 00:24:02,927
[SPEAKER_02]: made by the mayor to other committees as established by the charter and ordinances must be city residents.

289
00:24:02,967 --> 00:24:08,454
[SPEAKER_02]: That's another piece that came up should we require that people be city residents.

290
00:24:10,702 --> 00:24:19,205
[SPEAKER_02]: if a member resigns, removes from the city, or is otherwise unable to complete the term, the mayor shall fill such resulting vacancy.

291
00:24:19,945 --> 00:24:28,188
[SPEAKER_02]: So that actually doesn't require the mayor, but it kind of encourages the mayor to make sure that the mayor gets the word out, right?

292
00:24:29,169 --> 00:24:37,812
[SPEAKER_02]: So it just speaks to an intention that recruitment efforts be made, you know, significant recruitment efforts be made.

293
00:24:39,663 --> 00:24:43,245
[SPEAKER_02]: And I know that that's sort of come up, I think, in the city in general.

294
00:24:43,265 --> 00:24:46,907
[SPEAKER_02]: So I just want to just throw out, do we want to include some language like that?

295
00:24:50,789 --> 00:24:51,250
[SPEAKER_04]: I like it.

296
00:24:51,270 --> 00:24:53,031
[SPEAKER_04]: I think it'd be great to include it.

297
00:24:54,992 --> 00:24:55,392
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah.

298
00:24:55,592 --> 00:25:05,438
[SPEAKER_04]: And honestly, even the specification that appointments should be voters, I think, well, should it be residents or voters?

299
00:25:05,998 --> 00:25:07,339
[SPEAKER_02]: This says residents, but

300
00:25:08,581 --> 00:25:08,821
[SPEAKER_04]: Okay.

301
00:25:09,221 --> 00:25:16,845
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, that must be, I mean, you could say registered voters, but I don't know.

302
00:25:18,466 --> 00:25:27,031
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, the difference is that would allow the mayor to appoint, say, like a non-citizen who resides in Medford, which I think is probably good.

303
00:25:27,191 --> 00:25:29,252
[SPEAKER_04]: So I think resident is good.

304
00:25:32,132 --> 00:25:37,316
[SPEAKER_02]: Oh, and this also says that the person has to stay living in the city.

305
00:25:37,797 --> 00:25:44,962
[SPEAKER_02]: So if the person moves, they can't serve on the multiple member body.

306
00:25:47,284 --> 00:25:49,065
[SPEAKER_00]: Right, which has come up recently.

307
00:25:51,127 --> 00:25:52,168
[SPEAKER_00]: Don, what do you think about this?

308
00:25:54,359 --> 00:26:00,441
[SPEAKER_03]: As far as the recruitment provision, I guess, to me, that feels like something that is more of a policy than something that should be in a charter.

309
00:26:01,062 --> 00:26:01,882
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, okay.

310
00:26:04,083 --> 00:26:07,404
[SPEAKER_03]: As far as residents go, I agree with Davidi.

311
00:26:07,784 --> 00:26:11,785
[SPEAKER_03]: You know, there are people who aren't citizens that could bring a lot of value.

312
00:26:12,886 --> 00:26:13,486
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah.

313
00:26:14,486 --> 00:26:16,427
[SPEAKER_03]: And then, you know, it's funny, I'll be candid.

314
00:26:16,447 --> 00:26:19,608
[SPEAKER_03]: So I grew up and lived in Malden for a long time, and I had to leave the

315
00:26:20,897 --> 00:26:23,980
[SPEAKER_03]: the library board of trustees when I moved because I was no longer a resident.

316
00:26:24,020 --> 00:26:29,504
[SPEAKER_03]: So I do have some bias, but I would have loved to stay on if I could.

317
00:26:30,645 --> 00:26:34,548
[SPEAKER_03]: I understand that it's an issue in the city, but I don't know.

318
00:26:34,588 --> 00:26:43,956
[SPEAKER_04]: We can probably leave some wiggle room and say you have to be a resident to be appointed and not say that you have to be on the committee.

319
00:26:44,876 --> 00:26:47,819
[SPEAKER_03]: I didn't think of that, but I actually think that's, I think that's a good idea.

320
00:26:48,608 --> 00:26:52,753
[SPEAKER_02]: Well, what we can do is we can say that you have to be a resident to be appointed.

321
00:26:52,813 --> 00:26:58,860
[SPEAKER_02]: And then, I mean, these positions tend to have terms, right?

322
00:26:59,421 --> 00:27:01,243
[SPEAKER_02]: Ours doesn't because it's an ad hoc committee.

323
00:27:01,303 --> 00:27:04,907
[SPEAKER_02]: But like, so if you moved six months before your term was up,

324
00:27:05,942 --> 00:27:11,765
[SPEAKER_02]: this provision as written would require you to leave the body.

325
00:27:11,825 --> 00:27:20,048
[SPEAKER_02]: But if we left out that part, the person would have to be a member to be appointed, but it wouldn't necessarily mean that they couldn't finish out their term.

326
00:27:21,269 --> 00:27:21,569
[SPEAKER_02]: Eunice?

327
00:27:23,190 --> 00:27:35,275
[SPEAKER_00]: I mean, you have some boards there, like the Zoning Board and the Community Board, which are making decisions that are hugely impactful on Medford.

328
00:27:36,176 --> 00:27:39,278
[SPEAKER_00]: I would think that you would want a resident.

329
00:27:40,198 --> 00:27:46,201
[SPEAKER_00]: On those committees, I mean, even this committee in and of itself, we're making huge.

330
00:27:46,982 --> 00:27:53,986
[SPEAKER_00]: You know, life changing to the city decisions that we're bringing back to for voting.

331
00:27:54,988 --> 00:28:18,316
[SPEAKER_00]: I would think that, I feel pretty strongly that one needs to be a resident to serve on any committee in the city, unless there's a compelling reason, like it's something that's more chamber of commerce-ish, serving the business district or something like that, and it's somebody who has a business in the city.

332
00:28:20,878 --> 00:28:33,109
[SPEAKER_00]: I'm, you know, I feel pretty strongly that somebody should be at minimum a resident and I would also wonder about other qualifications for some of the boards as well.

333
00:28:34,910 --> 00:28:38,734
[SPEAKER_00]: You know, as I said, so many things have huge impact.

334
00:28:41,727 --> 00:28:43,848
[SPEAKER_00]: I haven't seen anything.

335
00:28:43,868 --> 00:28:51,211
[SPEAKER_00]: The application to join a board, which we all filled out to be on this, is kind of sparse.

336
00:28:52,111 --> 00:28:59,534
[SPEAKER_00]: I would think that some of the boards and commissions, certain qualifications would be required to sit on them.

337
00:29:01,240 --> 00:29:20,553
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, I think maybe that gets into what John was mentioning, that like there's certain things that maybe aren't charter material, because we can't like, I mean, I mean, John, you make a good point, even saying that this little recruitment paragraph might even be a little bit, you know, more like policy.

338
00:29:23,134 --> 00:29:25,696
[SPEAKER_02]: So I feel like those are more policy issues.

339
00:29:28,233 --> 00:29:40,015
[SPEAKER_02]: And it's hard, I think it's hard when we're doing this to sort of sometimes think, you know, because, you know, putting too much in the charter almost could not be a good thing to, you know.

340
00:29:40,855 --> 00:29:44,256
[SPEAKER_02]: So, I don't know.

341
00:29:45,196 --> 00:29:55,578
[SPEAKER_02]: But, and even the boards you named, I mean, one thing that's unclear, and this came up at the full committee meeting is,

342
00:29:56,906 --> 00:30:00,907
[SPEAKER_02]: which boards are going to actually be governed by this provision of the charter.

343
00:30:02,127 --> 00:30:14,570
[SPEAKER_02]: Because I don't necessarily think we need to know exactly which ones are in order to write this provision of the charter, because some of them are formed by state law and some of them aren't.

344
00:30:15,350 --> 00:30:21,272
[SPEAKER_02]: So, but I don't know if the ones you mentioned, you know, they could even be governed by state law.

345
00:30:22,292 --> 00:30:22,692
[SPEAKER_00]: We don't know.

346
00:30:26,331 --> 00:30:27,031
[SPEAKER_00]: Maybe John knows.

347
00:30:28,412 --> 00:30:42,377
[SPEAKER_04]: Eunice, I have to say, with all the sympathy for John's thing, you're probably right that you should have to be a resident to serve and not just be appointed.

348
00:30:42,397 --> 00:30:44,758
[SPEAKER_04]: OK.

349
00:30:45,118 --> 00:30:52,781
[SPEAKER_04]: Especially given how famously flimsy American residency law is to begin with, right?

350
00:30:56,068 --> 00:30:56,568
[SPEAKER_04]: That's true.

351
00:30:56,588 --> 00:31:16,345
[SPEAKER_00]: I mean, I think it's, you know, admirable on the one hand that, you know, because John grew up in Malden, that he'd want to stay on a board where in a place that he cares so much about, you know, be like, if I moved from Medford to Malden, I grew up here, you know, and I'd want to maybe stay and finish what I started.

352
00:31:16,925 --> 00:31:18,607
[SPEAKER_00]: But on the other hand, you know,

353
00:31:19,788 --> 00:31:29,395
[SPEAKER_00]: Is anybody serving on a board or commission part of the job in and of itself is to make decisions for the city or make recommendations?

354
00:31:29,996 --> 00:31:32,678
[SPEAKER_00]: And I think at bare minimum, you need to be a resident to do that.

355
00:31:36,000 --> 00:31:47,831
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay, so this came up as it came up at our full committee meeting, but it also came up again as part of the language from the fall river charter, but also included the recruitment materials.

356
00:31:47,931 --> 00:31:48,112
[SPEAKER_02]: So.

357
00:31:50,385 --> 00:31:53,488
[SPEAKER_02]: David, you said you thought it would be nice to include the recruitment stuff.

358
00:31:53,528 --> 00:31:55,770
[SPEAKER_02]: John, you said, well, that's more policy.

359
00:31:56,191 --> 00:32:02,577
[SPEAKER_02]: And I kind of, now that I, even though I thought it would be a great idea, I'm sort of maybe agreeing with John now.

360
00:32:02,677 --> 00:32:03,037
[SPEAKER_02]: I don't know.

361
00:32:04,278 --> 00:32:06,761
[SPEAKER_04]: But- I think we should definitely include the parts.

362
00:32:07,481 --> 00:32:09,844
[SPEAKER_04]: There were some parts of it that were the mayor's shell.

363
00:32:10,805 --> 00:32:11,225
[SPEAKER_02]: Yes.

364
00:32:11,986 --> 00:32:12,947
[SPEAKER_04]: The mayor's shell.

365
00:32:13,527 --> 00:32:15,049
[SPEAKER_04]: Annually post on- I think those parts are great.

366
00:32:15,997 --> 00:32:22,142
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay, so David, can you add, you have this memo that we got, right?

367
