543
00:49:24,431 --> 00:49:34,654
[SPEAKER_04]: Um, I like this, this section, the section that just says, you know, the, the city council's gonna pass an ordinance saying how much they get paid.

544
00:49:36,494 --> 00:49:38,275
[SPEAKER_03]: Um, that's my inclination.

545
00:49:39,133 --> 00:49:44,136
[SPEAKER_03]: You know, I'd be interested to know the, you know, if the call center wants to weigh in on the practicalities, I'd be really interested.

546
00:49:44,196 --> 00:49:47,017
[SPEAKER_03]: But, I mean, this language doesn't account for it.

547
00:49:47,117 --> 00:49:48,838
[SPEAKER_03]: The Watertown Charter is pretty new, I think.

548
00:49:49,459 --> 00:49:50,199
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, I think it is.

549
00:49:50,219 --> 00:49:54,782
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay, so David, are you going to add that language too?

550
00:49:55,960 --> 00:49:56,761
[SPEAKER_04]: I'll add that as well.

551
00:49:57,462 --> 00:50:04,411
[SPEAKER_04]: Do we want to then drop the clerk of the council or do we want to keep both of these kind of clerk of the council plus staff?

552
00:50:04,712 --> 00:50:05,573
[SPEAKER_04]: We won't call them additional.

553
00:50:05,613 --> 00:50:08,557
[SPEAKER_02]: I think we're just talking, we're just going with staff.

554
00:50:09,157 --> 00:50:10,399
[SPEAKER_02]: Does that sound right?

555
00:50:10,860 --> 00:50:11,140
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah.

556
00:50:11,300 --> 00:50:13,002
[SPEAKER_04]: And that means dropping the clerk of the council.

557
00:50:13,612 --> 00:50:14,152
[SPEAKER_00]: I think so.

558
00:50:14,712 --> 00:50:36,217
[SPEAKER_00]: I would leave it as open as possible because different editions of the council, I mean, this group seems to want, um, you know, uh, solicitor or something or their own legal council, but three councils down the road may feel like they need something more or something different.

559
00:50:36,877 --> 00:50:38,657
[SPEAKER_00]: So I think leaving it, you know, open.

560
00:50:40,278 --> 00:50:40,458
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah.

561
00:50:43,562 --> 00:50:44,663
[SPEAKER_02]: You know, I agree with that.

562
00:50:44,683 --> 00:50:49,126
[SPEAKER_04]: Although I'm super comfortable with the just calling it staff.

563
00:50:49,647 --> 00:50:50,227
[SPEAKER_04]: I think so.

564
00:50:50,287 --> 00:50:56,492
[SPEAKER_04]: The question I'm asking is, in Watertown, we see Section B is Berkeley Council and Section D is additional staff.

565
00:50:57,092 --> 00:51:00,174
[SPEAKER_04]: Do we want both of those sections or just Section D?

566
00:51:01,656 --> 00:51:05,659
[SPEAKER_02]: I feel like we just said just it wouldn't be called additional, obviously.

567
00:51:05,679 --> 00:51:06,279
[SPEAKER_04]: Right.

568
00:51:06,499 --> 00:51:06,699
Sure.

569
00:51:07,220 --> 00:51:07,480
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah.

570
00:51:08,160 --> 00:51:09,301
[SPEAKER_04]: How do you feel about that, John?

571
00:51:10,082 --> 00:51:10,182
[SPEAKER_03]: Oh.

572
00:51:11,344 --> 00:51:11,984
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm fine with that.

573
00:51:12,064 --> 00:51:21,989
[SPEAKER_03]: I guess my only question then is, is the city clerk by default somewhere the clerk of, who will play that role?

574
00:51:22,009 --> 00:51:23,070
[SPEAKER_03]: Does that make sense?

575
00:51:23,110 --> 00:51:24,310
[SPEAKER_02]: The clerk of the council?

576
00:51:24,850 --> 00:51:30,553
[SPEAKER_03]: Does the city clerk necessarily play the, effectively the clerk of the council role by default in some way?

577
00:51:30,573 --> 00:51:32,314
[SPEAKER_03]: Because that's who's the clerk of the council now.

578
00:51:33,474 --> 00:51:33,715
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah.

579
00:51:33,915 --> 00:51:40,138
[SPEAKER_03]: So maybe we'd want to create flexibility to just say, you know, I don't know, the additional staff.

580
00:51:41,527 --> 00:51:43,648
[SPEAKER_02]: I mean, we're not getting rid of the city clerk.

581
00:51:44,848 --> 00:51:45,288
[SPEAKER_03]: No, I know.

582
00:51:45,428 --> 00:51:46,328
[SPEAKER_03]: But it's interesting.

583
00:51:46,868 --> 00:51:51,810
[SPEAKER_03]: City council shall appoint blah, blah, blah, a person nominated by the council president who may be the city clerk.

584
00:51:52,390 --> 00:51:52,610
[SPEAKER_02]: Right.

585
00:51:52,630 --> 00:51:54,270
[SPEAKER_03]: I just think that's interesting.

586
00:51:54,690 --> 00:51:56,111
[SPEAKER_02]: So you're saying they don't have to?

587
00:51:56,811 --> 00:52:00,352
[SPEAKER_02]: I'm trying to see where their city clerk section is in here.

588
00:52:00,912 --> 00:52:02,372
[SPEAKER_02]: Is there a city clerk?

589
00:52:02,432 --> 00:52:08,274
[SPEAKER_04]: If you look in the chat, you can see what we currently have written out for ours as well.

590
00:52:13,632 --> 00:52:22,079
[SPEAKER_00]: I think that goes back to wondering what the job description of the city clerk currently is.

591
00:52:22,860 --> 00:52:25,161
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah.

592
00:52:25,802 --> 00:52:31,346
[SPEAKER_00]: How much of his time does he spend on a daily basis, weekly basis, whatever, on

593
00:52:33,774 --> 00:52:38,256
[SPEAKER_00]: city council activity versus what else does he do?

594
00:52:40,076 --> 00:52:49,320
[SPEAKER_00]: I think we all see him and know him as the guy who sits up there and next to the president and takes the minutes and so on and so forth.

595
00:52:50,520 --> 00:52:52,601
[SPEAKER_00]: How else does he fill his 40 hours in a week?

596
00:52:53,381 --> 00:52:57,023
[SPEAKER_02]: Well, this is from the charter, right, David?

597
00:52:58,303 --> 00:53:02,405
[SPEAKER_02]: The city council shall elect a city clerk to serve for a term of three years.

598
00:53:03,307 --> 00:53:04,727
[SPEAKER_04]: I don't remember where we got this.

599
00:53:04,807 --> 00:53:07,128
[SPEAKER_04]: This is just what I have in my notes that we agreed.

600
00:53:07,148 --> 00:53:08,528
[SPEAKER_04]: Oh, okay.

601
00:53:08,648 --> 00:53:09,588
[SPEAKER_02]: So we made a list of it.

602
00:53:09,888 --> 00:53:10,208
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay.

603
00:53:10,888 --> 00:53:12,449
[SPEAKER_02]: They do select an appointment.

604
00:53:13,209 --> 00:53:15,349
[SPEAKER_02]: Keeper of vital statistics of the city.

605
00:53:15,409 --> 00:53:16,909
[SPEAKER_02]: Custodian of the city seal.

606
00:53:17,069 --> 00:53:17,669
[SPEAKER_02]: All records.

607
00:53:18,029 --> 00:53:19,710
[SPEAKER_02]: Administer oath of office.

608
00:53:20,010 --> 00:53:22,070
[SPEAKER_02]: That is what the city clerk does now.

609
00:53:23,030 --> 00:53:25,751
[SPEAKER_02]: Issue licenses and permits as may be provided by law.

610
00:53:25,971 --> 00:53:26,951
[SPEAKER_02]: Powers and duties permit.

611
00:53:27,431 --> 00:53:27,631
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah.

612
00:53:29,011 --> 00:53:30,212
[SPEAKER_02]: He performs weddings.

613
00:53:30,352 --> 00:53:30,572
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay.

614
00:53:30,592 --> 00:53:32,572
[SPEAKER_02]: So we left the clerk of the council in.

615
00:53:34,695 --> 00:53:37,216
[SPEAKER_04]: So at the moment, Medford does not have a clerk of the council.

616
00:53:37,657 --> 00:53:41,059
[SPEAKER_04]: So in our last meeting, we added a clerk of the council.

617
00:53:41,880 --> 00:53:42,320
[SPEAKER_02]: Right.

618
00:53:42,480 --> 00:53:46,743
[SPEAKER_02]: And the clerk of the council, right now, those duties are done by the city clerk.

619
00:53:47,804 --> 00:53:48,004
[SPEAKER_03]: Right.

620
00:53:48,284 --> 00:53:48,764
[SPEAKER_02]: Pretty much.

621
00:53:50,045 --> 00:53:55,669
[SPEAKER_03]: Has that been an issue, having their own clerk, or just the need for staff?

622
00:53:57,107 --> 00:54:00,170
[SPEAKER_04]: No, I think when we discussed when we discussed adding a quirk.

623
00:54:00,350 --> 00:54:05,534
[SPEAKER_04]: It was the idea was it's one way to provide the city council with a staffer.

624
00:54:07,735 --> 00:54:11,138
[SPEAKER_03]: I would just keep I would, I would just say drop it and give them.

625
00:54:11,158 --> 00:54:13,079
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, I agree with that.

626
00:54:14,561 --> 00:54:19,845
[SPEAKER_02]: And and and then the staff is just, you know, it gives them more flexibility.

627
00:54:21,566 --> 00:54:21,906
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay.

628
00:54:22,607 --> 00:54:24,088
[SPEAKER_02]: All right.

629
00:54:25,032 --> 00:54:26,092
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay, so that's good.

630
00:54:27,872 --> 00:54:31,553
[SPEAKER_02]: What other questions did we have that were outstanding?

631
00:54:31,733 --> 00:54:32,533
[SPEAKER_02]: Let's see.

632
00:54:34,034 --> 00:54:45,235
[SPEAKER_02]: We talked about removal, qualifications, we made resident and that's... And what did we have?

633
00:54:46,636 --> 00:54:49,036
[SPEAKER_02]: Term limits, that was the other thing, term.

634
00:54:52,077 --> 00:54:54,177
[SPEAKER_02]: That is a huge one and I feel like

635
00:54:56,150 --> 00:55:04,976
[SPEAKER_02]: In some ways, I feel like maybe the term limits question should be taken up just with the whole committee.

636
00:55:04,996 --> 00:55:07,258
[SPEAKER_02]: What do you guys think?

637
00:55:07,278 --> 00:55:12,822
[SPEAKER_04]: My plan was just to write two years for all city councilors, four years for the mayor.

638
00:55:13,543 --> 00:55:23,089
[SPEAKER_04]: And then, again, when we ask for a review of the sections, I think even we as a group can say the first thing we would like to vote on is

639
00:55:25,307 --> 00:55:29,649
[SPEAKER_04]: the term limits issue for all three different groups that we're talking about, right?

640
00:55:30,249 --> 00:55:33,311
[SPEAKER_04]: At large, the ward based and the mayor.

641
00:55:33,831 --> 00:55:36,613
[SPEAKER_04]: So that's term length you're talking about, right?

642
00:55:36,933 --> 00:55:38,494
[SPEAKER_04]: Sorry, yes, term length.

643
00:55:38,834 --> 00:55:39,334
[SPEAKER_02]: That's okay.

644
00:55:39,495 --> 00:55:43,437
[SPEAKER_04]: Term limits, I'm completely against term limits, personally.

645
00:55:43,597 --> 00:55:44,017
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay, go ahead.

646
00:55:46,609 --> 00:55:59,935
[SPEAKER_02]: I feel like the term limits discussion, maybe we should just have that as a deliberation topic in a meeting with the whole committee, because there's a lot of... My experience is that people have strong feelings about it one way or the other.

647
00:55:59,955 --> 00:56:03,136
[SPEAKER_02]: I don't know.

648
00:56:03,776 --> 00:56:06,097
[SPEAKER_02]: So I feel like we should just have that discussion with the committee.

649
00:56:06,157 --> 00:56:06,978
[SPEAKER_02]: What do you think, John?

650
00:56:07,598 --> 00:56:08,698
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, I think so.

651
00:56:09,258 --> 00:56:10,259
[SPEAKER_03]: I mean, I'm with David.

652
00:56:10,779 --> 00:56:13,840
[SPEAKER_03]: I don't like them generally, but it's a value judgment.

653
00:56:14,020 --> 00:56:14,821
[SPEAKER_03]: You know, there's really no...

654
00:56:16,289 --> 00:56:19,574
[SPEAKER_03]: So I do think it would be important to put people the way in.

655
00:56:19,755 --> 00:56:23,100
[SPEAKER_03]: And if our recommendation is not to do them, then that makes our work easy.

656
00:56:23,260 --> 00:56:24,643
[SPEAKER_03]: Or we don't even have to recommend anything.

657
00:56:24,923 --> 00:56:26,886
[SPEAKER_03]: We can just say, you know, this is a sensitive issue.

658
00:56:27,828 --> 00:56:28,068
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah.

659
00:56:28,088 --> 00:56:29,109
[SPEAKER_03]: What are you guys thinking?

660
00:56:29,149 --> 00:56:30,150
[SPEAKER_02]: That's what I was thinking.

661
00:56:30,170 --> 00:56:32,412
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah.

662
00:56:33,313 --> 00:56:35,996
[SPEAKER_02]: And I might try to get some materials together.

663
00:56:36,176 --> 00:56:44,604
[SPEAKER_02]: I mean, you know, the studies, I looked for studies, and a lot of them are on state government and national government.

664
00:56:44,624 --> 00:56:46,766
[SPEAKER_02]: There aren't a lot on municipal government.

665
00:56:46,786 --> 00:56:49,248
[SPEAKER_03]: I had the same issue when I tried to look.

666
00:56:50,295 --> 00:56:59,178
[SPEAKER_02]: I did find that paper that was written by an NYU professor for a charter revision committee in New York City.

667
00:56:59,498 --> 00:57:09,922
[SPEAKER_02]: And so I was going to read through that and see if there was any... And he put a lot of references in that paper and see if there was any materials that... And so that's what I thought.

668
00:57:09,962 --> 00:57:18,444
[SPEAKER_02]: I'll just put some materials together, send them to the committee, and then maybe we can have that discussion as a committee because...

669
00:57:21,224 --> 00:57:23,585
[SPEAKER_04]: You might want to reach out to the Bloomberg Center at Harvard.

670
00:57:23,845 --> 00:57:26,665
[SPEAKER_04]: They do all kinds of city leadership nonsense.

671
00:57:27,885 --> 00:57:29,346
[SPEAKER_04]: So they may have resources.

672
00:57:30,846 --> 00:57:36,187
[SPEAKER_04]: And if you need somebody to talk to you there, I have a friend who works at that center.

673
00:57:36,427 --> 00:57:36,487
[SPEAKER_00]: OK.

674
00:57:36,507 --> 00:57:36,947
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you.

675
00:57:37,887 --> 00:57:43,329
[SPEAKER_00]: What about somebody in one of our first listening sessions mentioned, was it the Tisch Center?

676
00:57:44,389 --> 00:57:45,529
[SPEAKER_00]: Or is something up at Tufts?

677
00:57:45,789 --> 00:57:46,629
[SPEAKER_02]: That's at Tufts.

678
00:57:47,549 --> 00:57:49,210
[SPEAKER_02]: I thought, aren't they more international?

679
00:57:50,873 --> 00:57:52,994
[SPEAKER_02]: Policy, am I wrong about that?

680
00:57:53,535 --> 00:57:59,858
[SPEAKER_03]: The Fletcher School is the diplomacy school, but I think Tisch is trying to be state policy, not Tisch, excuse me.

681
00:58:00,499 --> 00:58:03,981
[SPEAKER_03]: I don't forget, but they have a new center that is state policy focused.

682
00:58:04,701 --> 00:58:08,083
[SPEAKER_03]: I've seen them cited in some articles, I believe.

683
00:58:08,103 --> 00:58:10,645
[SPEAKER_04]: Oh, the College of Civic Life.

684
00:58:11,725 --> 00:58:13,066
[SPEAKER_04]: I had no idea that existed.

685
00:58:13,726 --> 00:58:14,027
[SPEAKER_03]: It's new.

686
00:58:14,567 --> 00:58:16,168
[SPEAKER_03]: It's like maybe two years old, I think.

687
00:58:18,228 --> 00:58:40,081
[SPEAKER_02]: I mean, the little research, I mean, a lot of what I found echoes what you said at our last meeting, John, which is kind of like term limits tend to be really popular conceptually with voters, but the results that they think they're going to get from term limits don't usually.

688
00:58:41,232 --> 00:58:46,317
[SPEAKER_02]: aren't really realized by term.

689
00:58:46,678 --> 00:58:50,421
[SPEAKER_02]: So I'll try to come up with some information and share that.

690
00:58:50,501 --> 00:58:53,324
[SPEAKER_02]: And we'll just talk about that as a whole.

691
00:58:54,726 --> 00:58:56,848
[SPEAKER_02]: The other questions we had.

692
00:59:01,164 --> 00:59:16,109
[SPEAKER_02]: Well, we have that question about the, I feel like what we've come up with is actually given the city council president a good deal of power in terms of acting mayor, et cetera.

693
00:59:16,129 --> 00:59:28,733
[SPEAKER_02]: But it was, you know, how much power should the council president have in terms of behavior of counselors, attendance of counselors?

694
00:59:29,734 --> 00:59:30,254
[SPEAKER_02]: That came up.

695
00:59:31,377 --> 00:59:42,901
[SPEAKER_04]: Oh, I got to say, I'm sticking with what we said last time, which was just that, like, I don't think there's any power we can give the mayor or the city council or president in this case.

696
00:59:43,021 --> 00:59:45,161
[SPEAKER_04]: That isn't too much power.

697
00:59:45,401 --> 00:59:48,122
[SPEAKER_04]: Like, I don't think that there's any kind of middle of the road.

698
00:59:48,763 --> 00:59:53,264
[SPEAKER_04]: Aside from if we wanted to explicitly say, you know, the, the.

699
00:59:54,398 --> 01:00:00,800
[SPEAKER_04]: The city council can buy a all but unanimous vote, censure a member, but what does censure mean?

700
01:00:00,820 --> 01:00:02,920
[SPEAKER_04]: It means we don't like you.

701
01:00:02,940 --> 01:00:05,741
[SPEAKER_04]: They already know that they don't like you.

702
01:00:05,761 --> 01:00:07,681
[SPEAKER_02]: I think they can do that.

703
01:00:07,841 --> 01:00:09,662
[SPEAKER_04]: I don't know.

704
01:00:10,522 --> 01:00:11,322
[SPEAKER_02]: I agree with you.

705
01:00:11,722 --> 01:00:15,243
[SPEAKER_02]: And I feel like they can censure even without it being in the charter, right?

706
01:00:16,487 --> 01:00:25,011
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm just saying literally the only half, the only I think like reasonable thing we could write are things that yes, absolutely they can all work each to do.

707
01:00:25,211 --> 01:00:25,571
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah.

708
01:00:26,232 --> 01:00:26,472
[SPEAKER_00]: Eunice?

709
01:00:28,519 --> 01:00:38,909
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah, I was the 1 that, you know, brought up this in regards to, you know, the attendance issue in particular and 2 things come to mind.

710
01:00:39,330 --> 01:00:46,677
[SPEAKER_00]: I had been going back and forth with president morale on this for several months because of 1.

711
01:00:47,398 --> 01:00:53,001
[SPEAKER_00]: specific circumstance, and I just emailed her again last week.

712
01:00:53,241 --> 01:00:58,704
[SPEAKER_00]: I have not gotten a reply, and I know her term is drawing to a close, so I'm hoping that I do.

713
01:00:59,424 --> 01:01:14,952
[SPEAKER_00]: But, you know, I pointed out, you know, the attendance record that was in question, which she's well aware of, and I said, if there was anything that could be put in the charter that would have

714
01:01:17,336 --> 01:01:28,859
[SPEAKER_00]: Is there anything that she would have liked to have seen in the charter specifically that might've helped her, empowered her to deal with the issue in a different way than basically not dealing with it at all?

715
01:01:29,999 --> 01:01:39,762
[SPEAKER_00]: But the other thing that she pointed out to me months ago is that there's no provision in the charter at all that city councilors attend meetings.

716
01:01:40,982 --> 01:01:43,403
[SPEAKER_00]: So, you know,

717
01:01:44,498 --> 01:01:52,524
[SPEAKER_00]: The individual, you know, wasn't really in any sort of violation, um, because there was, so I'm wondering if there's.

718
01:01:52,544 --> 01:01:56,928
[SPEAKER_00]: Kind of going back to basics here is.

719
01:01:57,988 --> 01:02:02,772
[SPEAKER_00]: Maybe writing up a job description for city counselor.

720
01:02:03,413 --> 01:02:06,575
[SPEAKER_00]: You know, and school committee and mayor stating, you know.

721
01:02:08,296 --> 01:02:09,017
[SPEAKER_00]: That, you know.

722
01:02:10,195 --> 01:02:18,298
[SPEAKER_00]: anybody elected and serving must attend meetings because there was nothing that she could do.

723
01:02:18,598 --> 01:02:20,059
[SPEAKER_00]: And it was just kind of eye-opening.

724
01:02:23,100 --> 01:02:25,981
[SPEAKER_00]: There was no rule broken, no infraction.

725
01:02:26,861 --> 01:02:27,201
[SPEAKER_02]: Right.

726
01:02:29,022 --> 01:02:37,165
[SPEAKER_02]: I mean, the council makes its own rules in terms of how often they meet, et cetera, right?

727
01:02:38,781 --> 01:02:41,023
[SPEAKER_02]: So that's not, yeah.

728
01:02:43,785 --> 01:02:56,714
[SPEAKER_02]: I guess I see the issue, but I feel like it's really hard to address this because the reality of the situation is that the city councilors don't have a boss.

729
01:02:57,375 --> 01:03:00,017
[SPEAKER_02]: I mean, unless you call the voters their boss.

730
01:03:03,050 --> 01:03:11,155
[SPEAKER_02]: And so even the council president is only really presiding over meetings and doing other maybe tasks.

731
01:03:11,296 --> 01:03:14,978
[SPEAKER_02]: They're not the boss of the counselors, right?

732
01:03:15,118 --> 01:03:28,247
[SPEAKER_02]: I mean, it's not like an employment situation where... So I feel like it would just be really hard to address it in the charter.

733
01:03:28,267 --> 01:03:28,827
[SPEAKER_02]: I don't know.

734
01:03:29,127 --> 01:03:29,828
[SPEAKER_02]: What do you think, John?

735
01:03:31,038 --> 01:03:32,039
[SPEAKER_03]: No, I agree.

736
01:03:32,119 --> 01:03:35,040
[SPEAKER_03]: And, you know, the way I always think about, there's different ways.

737
01:03:35,401 --> 01:03:39,043
[SPEAKER_03]: And again, I'm not weighing in on the individual you're talking about, just generally.

738
01:03:39,063 --> 01:03:42,985
[SPEAKER_03]: I think there are different ways to be good at a legislative job.

739
01:03:43,385 --> 01:03:50,109
[SPEAKER_03]: You know, you can be somebody who slugs it out in the committees and generates these really thoughtful, informed ordinances.

740
01:03:50,915 --> 01:03:54,136
[SPEAKER_03]: You could be somebody who throws bombs and makes the case for things.

741
01:03:54,156 --> 01:03:57,857
[SPEAKER_03]: You know, both of those in a real way are a good way to be a city councilor.

742
01:03:57,877 --> 01:03:58,677
[SPEAKER_03]: You're doing your job.

743
01:03:58,857 --> 01:04:05,979
[SPEAKER_03]: Or you could just be someone who doesn't care about ordinances, and you just help the people in the community as a constituent relations person.

744
01:04:06,019 --> 01:04:08,579
[SPEAKER_03]: So, you know, I don't know.

745
01:04:10,320 --> 01:04:13,100
[SPEAKER_03]: I mean, to me, at this point, they're not anyone's, they don't have a boss.

746
01:04:13,820 --> 01:04:20,482
[SPEAKER_03]: And this is actually, this is why I like one-on-one races and awards, because then someone's not showing up,

747
01:04:21,415 --> 01:04:25,297
[SPEAKER_03]: At meetings, that's one person can make that case against another person.

748
01:04:25,797 --> 01:04:27,138
[SPEAKER_03]: This person doesn't need to show up for work.

749
01:04:28,399 --> 01:04:30,480
[SPEAKER_04]: Whereas now... And I think at the end of the day... Oh.

750
01:04:31,501 --> 01:04:33,301
[SPEAKER_03]: No, no, I'm just rambling now.

751
01:04:33,902 --> 01:04:39,685
[SPEAKER_04]: At the end of the day, like, you know, I'm trying to think through the rules we could set up, right?

752
01:04:39,945 --> 01:04:45,508
[SPEAKER_04]: You know, maybe they don't get paid or they get removed from their post if they miss five meetings.

753
01:04:45,868 --> 01:04:48,610
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, what's going to stop the city council president from

754
01:04:49,457 --> 01:04:54,920
[SPEAKER_04]: opening and closing five meetings in rapid succession to kick somebody who doesn't like off the council.

755
01:04:56,681 --> 01:05:07,127
[SPEAKER_04]: Okay, if they don't show up to a meeting for three months, well, you know, our nasty person who doesn't want to do their job is going to show up to one meeting every three months.

756
01:05:08,648 --> 01:05:11,189
[SPEAKER_04]: And that's not going to solve the problem.

757
01:05:11,609 --> 01:05:14,651
[SPEAKER_04]: In the same way, I mean, if we required them to show up to

758
01:05:16,252 --> 01:05:44,147
[SPEAKER_04]: uh every other meeting at a minimum right like you could just show up and pull out your phone and sit there plan uh candy crush the whole meeting and and that wouldn't really i don't think we can compel them to be good counselors um there's just and it's entirely possible that there's some angle that i'm missing but i i can't off the top of my head think of any angles that that would allow us to compel them to do their jobs

759
01:05:44,838 --> 01:06:11,741
[SPEAKER_00]: I mean, if this person were to have run again, given the fact that meetings are in-person, poorly attended by the residents, and not attended via Zoom by residents, if a counselor has enough buddies that think he's a nice guy, you know,

760
01:06:12,374 --> 01:06:20,839
[SPEAKER_00]: they could get elected again and continue the same behavior because 90% of the city isn't paying attention.

761
01:06:20,859 --> 01:06:24,201
[SPEAKER_04]: I think that's just democracy.

762
01:06:24,221 --> 01:06:26,803
[SPEAKER_04]: I think that's just democracy.

763
01:06:27,103 --> 01:06:33,187
[SPEAKER_04]: I wrote it as a joke, but maybe Article 11 should establish the city newspaper.

764
01:06:37,760 --> 01:06:39,661
[SPEAKER_04]: These are information problems.

765
01:06:41,002 --> 01:06:45,265
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm still mostly joking about establishing a newspaper in the charter.

766
01:06:47,187 --> 01:06:53,831
[SPEAKER_04]: But I think at the end of the day, in a democracy, if nobody's running against you to do that, like, it is what it is.

767
01:06:53,851 --> 01:06:57,133
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, I agree.

768
01:06:57,854 --> 01:07:02,877
[SPEAKER_02]: I mean, as unfortunate as it is, I don't think we can manage that in the charter.

769
01:07:03,578 --> 01:07:05,999
[SPEAKER_02]: Although, if you do hear back from

770
01:07:07,336 --> 01:07:12,459
[SPEAKER_02]: Nicole, and because you asked her a specific question, President Morrell.

771
01:07:12,479 --> 01:07:13,100
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah.

772
01:07:13,860 --> 01:07:22,246
[SPEAKER_02]: If she has a specific response, then it would be, you know, of course, we would be interested in hearing what her suggestions.

773
01:07:23,507 --> 01:07:32,693
[SPEAKER_02]: One thing that you reminded me of David, that now I can't find what is the information access is access to information.

774
01:07:35,612 --> 01:07:37,013
[SPEAKER_02]: Were we including this?

775
01:07:37,073 --> 01:07:39,955
[SPEAKER_02]: Had we already decided to include a section like this?

776
01:07:39,975 --> 01:07:42,017
[SPEAKER_04]: I think we had.

777
01:07:42,117 --> 01:07:43,378
[SPEAKER_04]: Let me double check.

778
01:07:46,080 --> 01:07:49,223
[SPEAKER_02]: I mean, this is a city with a city manager.

779
01:07:49,283 --> 01:07:51,464
[SPEAKER_02]: Obviously, we wouldn't do that.

780
01:07:51,645 --> 01:08:04,555
[SPEAKER_02]: But this addresses some of the concerns we've heard about, you know, the mayor not having to show up at city council meetings, et cetera.

781
01:08:06,035 --> 01:08:12,177
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah, so we definitely included somewhere that the city council can force the mayor to show up to meetings.

782
01:08:13,158 --> 01:08:14,158
[SPEAKER_04]: Okay.

783
01:08:14,718 --> 01:08:14,918
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah.

784
01:08:16,499 --> 01:08:18,800
[SPEAKER_04]: And where did we put that?

785
01:08:20,880 --> 01:08:26,022
[SPEAKER_02]: Because I think there's other charters too where it's a whole section, right?

786
01:08:26,502 --> 01:08:30,344
[SPEAKER_02]: It has to be 2-6 because that must have been in the generic charter too.

787
01:08:30,364 --> 01:08:30,784
[SPEAKER_02]: Let me see.

788
01:08:31,064 --> 01:08:33,865
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah, so we discussed oversight.

789
01:08:35,091 --> 01:08:42,296
[SPEAKER_04]: And the thing we said was compel mayoral attendance of meetings, plus city employees include multi-member bodies.

790
01:08:42,336 --> 01:08:47,579
[SPEAKER_04]: So you can also compel the, the attendance of members of multi-member bodies.

791
01:08:48,220 --> 01:08:53,143
[SPEAKER_04]: You have to give 10 days notice and a yearly state of the city report is what we have at the moment.

792
01:08:55,144 --> 01:08:56,905
[SPEAKER_04]: This does seem more complete.

793
01:08:57,166 --> 01:09:00,388
[SPEAKER_04]: So I might also, let's see.

794
01:09:01,890 --> 01:09:06,191
[SPEAKER_04]: And, you know, remember... I like section B here of this.

795
01:09:06,951 --> 01:09:08,971
[SPEAKER_04]: So it might be good to include that as well.

796
01:09:09,931 --> 01:09:14,292
[SPEAKER_04]: Or section A and B. Although subpoenaing still seems really intense.

797
01:09:14,872 --> 01:09:15,832
[SPEAKER_01]: It does seem intense.

798
01:09:16,252 --> 01:09:20,633
[SPEAKER_04]: I mean... So I might include section A and B without the subpoena bit.

799
01:09:21,273 --> 01:09:25,354
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, it's just a word in this context, right?

800
01:09:25,414 --> 01:09:29,315
[SPEAKER_02]: It's semantics, but it does give a certain feeling.

801
01:09:30,115 --> 01:09:30,395
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah.

802
01:09:32,461 --> 01:09:37,004
[SPEAKER_02]: Because they're not a legal body that's doing a legal subpoena.

803
01:09:38,125 --> 01:09:55,620
[SPEAKER_00]: I think having this section in there, and this is on my to-do list to bring up, is really important because one thing that you'll hear the council say time and time again is that they don't have any real authority to compel anybody to come before them.

804
01:09:56,120 --> 01:10:19,384
[SPEAKER_00]: If they wanted summons or subpoena or require or request or whatever word you want, the Department of Public Works to come before them to talk about potholes on Main Street, he doesn't have to, unless the mayor tells them to go show up and talk about the potholes on Main Street.

805
01:10:19,404 --> 01:10:23,085
[SPEAKER_00]: Right now, I think we've all heard,

806
01:10:25,402 --> 01:10:38,252
[SPEAKER_00]: things about the last election and the folks in the elections office don't necessarily have to answer to the city council or anybody doesn't.

807
01:10:38,532 --> 01:10:52,842
[SPEAKER_00]: So I think requiring not just the mayor, I think the mayor should be required to meet with the council maybe once a quarter in a committee of the whole

808
01:10:55,023 --> 01:11:13,098
[SPEAKER_00]: to talk about issues that come up, but I think that the council should also be able to request that any city employee or at least department head come before them to answer questions.

809
01:11:13,999 --> 01:11:14,239
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah.

810
01:11:14,419 --> 01:11:16,641
[SPEAKER_02]: I mean, that's basically what this section says.

811
01:11:19,507 --> 01:11:27,631
[SPEAKER_02]: It doesn't say, you know, so-and-so has to show up at the city council meetings every month or every six months or whatever.

812
01:11:27,651 --> 01:11:31,594
[SPEAKER_02]: It just says the city council can say, you gotta come before us, right?

813
01:11:31,914 --> 01:11:33,955
[SPEAKER_04]: Which I think is good.

814
01:11:33,975 --> 01:11:42,380
[SPEAKER_04]: I don't want to set a quarterly requirement and then hear a year later that it's too often or not often enough.

815
01:11:42,540 --> 01:11:48,503
[SPEAKER_04]: Let the city council decide how often they want the mayor to show up in the room with them.

816
01:11:49,187 --> 01:12:05,297
[SPEAKER_02]: I mean, yeah, you know, I mean, hopefully the council wouldn't abuse the power and call the mayor at every single meeting and say, you have to tell us this and this and this.

817
01:12:07,418 --> 01:12:13,962
[SPEAKER_02]: But, I mean, right now they do do this, except it's a request, right?

818
01:12:15,423 --> 01:12:16,744
[SPEAKER_02]: Whereas this makes it,

819
01:12:18,827 --> 01:12:24,051
[SPEAKER_02]: It just gives them that much more authority to say, you know, to require it.

820
01:12:24,211 --> 01:12:29,434
[SPEAKER_02]: And this specifically says the mayor, and the mayor doesn't specifically have to show up now.

821
01:12:32,296 --> 01:12:38,740
[SPEAKER_03]: I would happily take this whole section and put it in.

822
01:12:39,661 --> 01:12:44,844
[SPEAKER_02]: Even the subpoena witnesses administer oaths and require the production of evidence part?

823
01:12:44,864 --> 01:12:45,805
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah.

824
01:12:46,878 --> 01:12:49,079
[SPEAKER_04]: Actually, the more I think about it, yes.

825
01:12:49,559 --> 01:12:50,100
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm the same.

826
01:12:50,320 --> 01:12:51,580
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah.

827
01:12:52,201 --> 01:12:52,621
[SPEAKER_04]: I like it.

828
01:12:53,782 --> 01:12:54,142
[SPEAKER_02]: OK.

829
01:12:54,202 --> 01:12:57,603
[SPEAKER_02]: So will I need to send this link to you, David?

830
01:12:59,705 --> 01:13:00,465
[SPEAKER_02]: OK.

831
01:13:00,685 --> 01:13:01,145
[SPEAKER_01]: I've got it.

832
01:13:01,245 --> 01:13:01,405
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah.

833
01:13:01,505 --> 01:13:01,806
[SPEAKER_02]: OK.

834
01:13:01,826 --> 01:13:06,548
[SPEAKER_02]: So I have that you're going to modify that section, the access to information section.

835
01:13:06,568 --> 01:13:10,850
[SPEAKER_02]: We were just talking a little bit about rules, right?

836
01:13:17,382 --> 01:13:21,724
[SPEAKER_02]: There is a section that does address, but it's very vague.

837
01:13:22,044 --> 01:13:24,705
[SPEAKER_02]: It just says the council can adopt their rules.

838
01:13:28,746 --> 01:13:31,747
[SPEAKER_02]: And it says they have to have regular meetings, right?

839
01:13:31,767 --> 01:13:33,067
[SPEAKER_02]: Is that how you read that?

840
01:13:33,388 --> 01:13:35,788
[SPEAKER_02]: It doesn't say how often, it just says they have to be regular.

841
01:13:37,049 --> 01:13:46,412
[SPEAKER_00]: I wonder if we could include in there, and I'm thinking of this specifically, you know, well, maybe making it

842
01:13:47,312 --> 01:13:54,238
[SPEAKER_00]: blanket across all bodies, elected city council, school committee, anything else.

843
01:13:54,919 --> 01:14:12,034
[SPEAKER_00]: One of the complaints that I've heard is that the time that some of these meetings are scheduled at, particularly on the school committee side, where they're scheduling meetings at 4, 4.30, 5 o'clock in the afternoon, where the general public just simply can't attend.

844
01:14:12,394 --> 01:14:13,856
[SPEAKER_00]: I'm wondering if there's a way to

845
01:14:14,852 --> 01:14:25,634
[SPEAKER_00]: you know, under the rules of procedure indicate that, you know, meetings, you know, must not start any earlier than 6pm or something like that.

846
01:14:25,654 --> 01:14:39,497
[SPEAKER_04]: I wouldn't want, I don't, I think they need to have meetings when they can have meetings, but yeah, I don't want to take, I don't want to handcuff people that way, especially, I mean, man, if you, if you need to have a 12 hour day, like,

847
01:14:43,985 --> 01:14:53,852
[SPEAKER_04]: I think we have to trust our democratically elected officials to meet when they can meet and do what they got to do.

848
01:14:54,373 --> 01:14:58,836
[SPEAKER_00]: Basically eliminates public participation in a lot of cases.

849
01:15:00,938 --> 01:15:02,819
[SPEAKER_02]: I mean, a four o'clock meeting, you're saying?

850
01:15:02,839 --> 01:15:02,919
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah.

851
01:15:06,670 --> 01:15:17,518
[SPEAKER_04]: I mean, I think in the same way, if you, like, you know, there are people who work night shifts, there are people who need to put their kids to bed at 7pm, right?

852
01:15:17,558 --> 01:15:18,418
[SPEAKER_04]: Like, they can't attend.

853
01:15:18,538 --> 01:15:24,923
[SPEAKER_04]: It's, I don't think that, and those norms could also change, right?

854
01:15:25,063 --> 01:15:32,068
[SPEAKER_04]: Like, I would be very uncomfortable putting something like that into the charter.

855
01:15:34,491 --> 01:15:38,774
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, I agree and I just think we have to be careful about micromanaging.

856
01:15:42,757 --> 01:15:58,868
[SPEAKER_02]: The other thing about this section here, like what I've noticed is some of these sections that I look at and I see them in charters and then I see them, some sections of the charters are lifted straight from state law and they're just sort of reiterated in the charter.

857
01:15:59,968 --> 01:16:02,030
[SPEAKER_02]: And I don't know if this is one of them,

858
01:16:06,630 --> 01:16:16,076
[SPEAKER_03]: Milva, if the subpoena issue makes you uncomfortable, Melrose does not mention it, but looks like Framingham, Watertown, Weymouth do.

859
01:16:17,197 --> 01:16:18,858
[SPEAKER_03]: I wonder to what extent it's an inherent power.

860
01:16:18,878 --> 01:16:20,339
[SPEAKER_03]: I really don't know.

861
01:16:23,301 --> 01:16:23,821
[SPEAKER_02]: I don't know.

862
01:16:23,841 --> 01:16:33,347
[SPEAKER_02]: I mean, it's not just, it says subpoena witnesses administer oaths and require the production

863
01:16:34,107 --> 01:16:34,467
[SPEAKER_02]: evidence.

864
01:16:35,368 --> 01:16:37,249
[SPEAKER_02]: So I don't know.

865
01:16:37,269 --> 01:16:40,450
[SPEAKER_02]: I mean, that's a good thing.

866
01:16:40,831 --> 01:16:43,072
[SPEAKER_04]: We don't want people lying to the city council.

867
01:16:43,312 --> 01:16:46,454
[SPEAKER_04]: And we want the city council to be able to require the production of evidence.

868
01:16:46,734 --> 01:16:50,696
[SPEAKER_04]: So like, I think it is scary language.

869
01:16:50,976 --> 01:16:52,137
[SPEAKER_04]: It makes me uncomfortable.

870
01:16:52,177 --> 01:16:54,398
[SPEAKER_04]: But I think it's also exactly the thing.

871
01:16:55,479 --> 01:16:57,300
[SPEAKER_04]: At least I would mean for it to say so.

872
01:17:00,314 --> 01:17:03,998
[SPEAKER_02]: Well, we can let's let's leave it and see what everybody else says too.

873
01:17:05,780 --> 01:17:11,366
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay, so the only other piece was we talked about term.

874
01:17:13,230 --> 01:17:20,495
[SPEAKER_02]: I just wanted to throw out, we were talking about term lengths and we said we were going to suggest four years for mayor and leaving city council at two.

875
01:17:21,096 --> 01:17:30,963
[SPEAKER_02]: But we did talk about potentially, I think the only city I found that has the split terms for city councilors was Framingham.

876
01:17:31,043 --> 01:17:34,206
[SPEAKER_02]: And they have four years for at-large and two for ward.

877
01:17:35,426 --> 01:17:38,389
[SPEAKER_02]: And that was a possibility that people had mentioned.

878
01:17:39,189 --> 01:17:41,271
[SPEAKER_02]: But I only found one city that does it.

879
01:17:41,691 --> 01:17:42,652
[SPEAKER_02]: You sure Melrose doesn't?

880
01:17:44,240 --> 01:17:49,846
[SPEAKER_02]: It's possible, and because, you know, things like this tend to change, so maybe I didn't see that.

881
01:17:50,186 --> 01:17:50,787
[SPEAKER_02]: It's possible.

882
01:17:50,807 --> 01:18:04,600
[SPEAKER_04]: I mean, if y'all are comfortable with it, and from what I remember, our last discussion sounded like you were, I think we should recommend exactly what you just said, and also recommend let's have those discussions and those votes, right?

883
01:18:05,040 --> 01:18:06,362
[SPEAKER_04]: Let's talk about all three.

884
01:18:06,382 --> 01:18:06,462
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah.

885
01:18:08,611 --> 01:18:15,741
[SPEAKER_04]: Uh, the term, yeah, just go into it with the assumption that that's going to be something further discussed by the larger committee.

886
01:18:16,362 --> 01:18:17,924
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay, um.

887
01:18:19,506 --> 01:18:19,726
[SPEAKER_02]: So.

888
01:18:21,306 --> 01:18:23,847
[SPEAKER_02]: I was going to say, we're talking about the term lengths.

889
01:18:24,448 --> 01:18:48,338
[SPEAKER_02]: One of the things to think about, too, with the term lengths, and it's hard to really know the answers to these questions, but is the effect of term lengths on, well, there's budget issues with elections, but now we have elections every two years anyway, so that's, we wouldn't be putting another burden on the city, like with staggered terms, for instance, might do that.

890
01:18:49,338 --> 01:19:02,047
[SPEAKER_02]: But it's also the voter turnout and things like that, that an off-year election that doesn't have the mayor, say, would definitely change the outlook for people.

891
01:19:02,067 --> 01:19:04,209
[SPEAKER_02]: No, that's a real concern.

892
01:19:18,041 --> 01:19:20,743
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, so what do you think?

893
01:19:22,684 --> 01:19:35,230
[SPEAKER_04]: I think we're already also, like, the thing that makes the concern even more valid is the fact that, you know, in a ward election, we're now talking about hundreds of votes, possibly total.

894
01:19:35,970 --> 01:19:39,712
[SPEAKER_04]: Exactly.

895
01:19:40,173 --> 01:19:42,354
[SPEAKER_04]: But on the flip side, in a ward election,

896
01:19:43,336 --> 01:19:54,301
[SPEAKER_04]: each city councilor has a very small number of houses that they, whose doors they have to knock, and people they have to excite, and people they have to pull out.

897
01:19:54,541 --> 01:20:01,944
[SPEAKER_04]: Which is, you know, that's part of what makes me personally uncomfortable with wards.

898
01:20:02,384 --> 01:20:05,346
[SPEAKER_04]: I don't have a strong feeling, I'm uncomfortable with both options, right?

899
01:20:05,366 --> 01:20:07,467
[SPEAKER_04]: They're both difficult.

900
01:20:08,927 --> 01:20:12,909
[SPEAKER_04]: But I certainly think four years is much too long for city councilors.

901
01:20:13,863 --> 01:20:14,324
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah.

902
01:20:14,644 --> 01:20:16,786
[SPEAKER_04]: Especially if we have one who's not doing the job.

903
01:20:17,387 --> 01:20:23,313
[SPEAKER_04]: And two years is, I cannot imagine our city functioning if we change mayors every two years.

904
01:20:23,493 --> 01:20:26,817
[SPEAKER_04]: I can barely imagine the city functioning if we change mayor every four years.

905
01:20:27,437 --> 01:20:27,858
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah.

906
01:20:28,760 --> 01:20:31,623
[SPEAKER_04]: So, like, I think these are very reasonable numbers.

907
01:20:31,663 --> 01:20:32,704
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, I agree with you.

908
01:20:32,744 --> 01:20:49,942
[SPEAKER_02]: City Council, it just, four years does kind of feel long, but then they're at, you know, the election turnout issue, then you, you know, but interestingly, and I know this is going to be, it's in the, I filed the interview report in our interviews folder, but Paulette and I,

909
01:20:51,003 --> 01:21:03,134
[SPEAKER_02]: interviewed the superintendent, and she was very flexible on everything, but the one thing she probably said made the strongest statement on was that she thought that the school committee member should have four-year terms.

